          "body": "The extended inventory of Temple objects (25:13-17) is not antiquarian detail. Every item named — the bronze pillars Jachin and Boaz (1 Kings 7:15-22), the bronze sea, the stands, the pots, the snuffers, the firepans — had been described in detail at their creation in 1 Kings 7. Their original description was a hymn to God's glory dwelling among His people; their listing here is a funeral dirge. The two great pillars stood at the Temple entrance for 370 years. Their height (eighteen cubits each, 25:17) is noted as they are broken to pieces for transport. The narrator's note that their weight was 'beyond weight' (25:16) — immeasurable at their creation — is now immeasurable rubble. The burning of the Temple in 25:9 is the chapter's theological apex: the Shekinah glory that departed in Ezekiel 10-11 has now been followed by the physical structure itself. The place where heaven and earth met in Israel is ash."
