          "body": "The brief episode of Gedaliah (25:22-26) is a portrait of what submission to divine judgment could have looked like — and didn't. Gedaliah's appointment connects to one of the most pro-Jeremiah families in Judean history: his father Ahikam had protected Jeremiah from death (Jer. 26:24), and his grandfather Shaphan had brought the rediscovered Torah scroll to King Josiah (2 Kings 22:8-10). Gedaliah counsels submission and peace: 'Do not be afraid of the servants of the Chaldeans; live in the land and serve the king of Babylon, and it will be well with you' (25:24). This is almost verbatim Jeremiah's counsel (Jer. 27:11-12; 40:9). Yet within months, nationalist pride — embodied in Ishmael, of the royal family, who cannot bear the humiliation of submission — assassinates Gedaliah and destroys the possibility of ordered remnant life. The entire remaining population then flees to Egypt (25:26), choosing fear over faith, choosing Egypt over the land. The remnant's failure is the last earthly option closing."
